age, his life as a young single parent in Manhattan in the nineties, visits and conversations with a cousin dying of AIDS—creating a montage that has the feel of history as lived experience. Bookending this sequence are shorter lyrics that span times and locations, from Nairobi to the Native American villages of New Mexico. In the dynamic, sensual language of these poems, we are reminded that the history of atrocity, trauma, and forgetting is both global and ancient; but we are reminded, too, of the beauty and richness of culture and the resilience of love.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPoetry. 7aPOETRY / General.2bisacsh  apoem, poetry, pueblo, new mexico, creative writing, mfa, armenia, armenian, genocide, poetic form, formal poet, end rhyme, christmas, dance, television, journalism, contemporary, modern, marriage, divorce, relationships, aids, death, tragedy, manhattan, single parent, nairobi, native american, trauma, healing, global, international, aleppo, borders, borderlands, history, historical, love, romance, silk road, finaches, los angeles.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226207179423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226207179/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles